Frozen yet alive: beneath the ice, large schools of fish explore with a freedom that only the winter season offers. While predation from other fish species remains a threat, their icy ceiling protects them from numerous diving animals, including birds and mammals, that will have to wait until the ice thaws for another fish meal. In water temperatures hovering above freezing, life moves slower, including for these freshwater emerald shiners in Ontario’s Lake Simcoe. Full video link in bio. #frozenlake @kevinbiskaborn

Mink on the brink: this semiaquatic mammal is on a mission — it's hungry! But in order to dive and hunt for food in the water, it first needs to locate a suitable opening in the ice. Minks must exploit this water access before plummeting temperatures freeze it shut until the spring thaw. #mink @kevinbiskaborn
Waking up after a snowstorm. #whitetaildeer @kevinbiskaborn
A successful hunt. A failed escape. The struggle to survive. #barredowl #chipmunk @kevinbiskaborn

An epic chase, and the most incredible wildlife hunting footage I’ve ever captured. From several springs back, as the snow was melting, a chipmunk emerged only to be immediately and relentlessly hunted by a barred owl.

The actual duration of the hunt, from initial discovery to the successful catch, was over an hour. For the majority of that time, the owl patiently waited on a nearby tree while the chipmunk squeaked from its hiding spot. As soon as the chipmunk got the courage to emerge and make a run for it, the owl would pounce again.

It was a difficult situation for both animals, clearly representing the struggle that happens each day in nature. The chipmunk could not always see the owl, and eventually had to venture out, and then the owl was clever and persistent at flushing the chipmunk out of its hiding spots. For the owl, it had its work cut out for it. Not only was it attempting to hunt in the day - giving up its nighttime advantage - but it also had to dodge shrubs, trees and low-hanging branches while pursuing a prey that has both speed and quick maneuverability. Neither animal had it easy!

Regretfully, the visual quality of the footage is poor as I was not prepared for this unexpected encounter at the time. It’s also zoomed in as it was filmed at a distance.

The full chase sequence is available on YouTube and through the link in my bio. I’m often asked, “how did I manage to get this footage?” and “did I bait the owl with a captive chipmunk or is it a pet owl?”.

This pursuit was already in progress when, thanks to luck, I stumbled upon it. I began filming from a respectful distance with the equipment I had at the time. I never expected to witness this chase on that day. During two of the sequences, the animals unpredictably and rapidly approached my position at which point I quickly backed off. Both the owl and the chipmunk were wild and were not baited. Both animals were so focused on survival (the owl getting a meal and the chipmunk not becoming one), that I was hardly noticed.

It was an incredible experience watching this and to be able to film it. #barredowl #chipmunk @kevinbiskaborn

Endless feast: a loon eats its fill of fish underwater in Ontario’s Lake Simcoe. Spring has arrived and the ice covering the water has melted. The giant schools of fish are no longer protected from the swarms of migratory waterbirds descending on the lake before they head north for the summer. #loon @kevinbiskaborn
